h as Saul's madness, David's murder of Uriah, the rape of Tamar, and the rebellion of Absalom, the book's author deepens our understanding not only of the necessity of sovereign rule but also of its costs-to the people it is intended to protect and to those who wield it. What emerges from the meticulous analysis of these narratives includes such themes as the corrosive grip of power on those who hold and compete for power; the ways in which political violence unleashed by the sovereign on his own subjects is rooted in the paranoia of the isolated ruler and the deniability fostered by hierarchical action through proxies; and the intensity with which the tragic conflict between political loyalty and family loyalty explodes when the ruler's bloodline is made into the guarantor of the all-important continuity of sovereign power.The Beginning of Politics is a timely meditation on the dark side of sovereign power and the enduring dilemmas of statecraft.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiblexCriticism, Interpretation, Etc.xO. T. Historical Books. 0aPolitics in the Bible. 0aPower (Social sciences)xBiblical teaching. 0aPower (Social sciences). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aHolmes, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054332240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400884896zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400884896423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400884896.jpg  a978-3-11-054332-2  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEB